passages.text: Reflecting FY2024 results and currently solid cloud sales, we raise our earnings estimates and maintain our price target of \(\yen 16,000\) through December 2026 (previously through December 2025). Our price target is based on a P/E of slightly above 26x and our FY2026 EPS estimate of \(\yen 605\) (previously P/E of 30x and our EPS estimate of \(\yen 530\) ). We think this P/E, which is within the stock's average range since 2020 but above the IT services average of 20x, is justified by the company's defensive characteristics, higher operating margin than competitors', and high ROE. FY2025 guidance calls for 6- 10% growth in sales, above our estimate (+2- 6%), and solid 7% YoY growth in recognition within a year of recovery point objective (RPO; \(\yen 283.7\) billion, \(+11.5\%\) YoY). While on- premise sales are generally expected to decline over the medium to long term, we believe demand is currently strong in the government and financial domains. Additionally, while a special dividend at end- FY2026 is the market consensus view, we expect an end- FY2025 special dividend of \(\yen 572\) share in addition to the regular dividend of \(\yen 208\) share (total: \(\yen 780\) share). However, special dividends tend to be announced after the ex- dividend date, so we would caution against excessively high expectations.

- FY2025 and 1Q earnings: We forecast FY2025 sales of \(\yen 282.0\) billion \((+7\%)\) operating profit of \(\yen 94.5\) billion \((+8.8\%)\) , and EPS of \(\yen 519\) \((+9.5\%)\) versus guidance for 6-10% sales growth and EPS of \(\yen 490-505\) . For the main cloud & license segment, we forecast sales at \(\yen 241.3\) billion \((+8.2\%)\) , with on-premise licenses accounting for \(\yen 8.8\) billion \((-1.1\%)\) , cloud services \(\yen 78.1\) billion \((+26\%)\) , and license support \(\yen 115.1\) billion \((+2.4\%)\) , with cloud services driving sales. We forecast 1Q sales of \(\yen 64.4\) billion and operating profit of \(\yen 21.6\) billion, in line with Bloomberg consensus estimates. We expect a reactionary decline from the rush demand spike ahead of the price hike in FY2024, but expect this to be offset by sales growth for cloud services.

The company, the Japanese subsidiary of de facto parent company Oracle, is a distributor of Oracle products. It currently has an over- \(40\%\) share of Japan's database market and ranks an estimated second or third in Japan's cloud infrastructure business. As a distributor with an asset- light business model, it has had an operating margin of over \(30\%\) for the past several years, and its RoE has been about \(30\%\) for over 15 years because management actively returns capital to shareholders.

We set a price target of ¥16,000 (by end- 2026) based on slightly above 26x our FY2026 EPS estimate of ¥605. We think this P/E, which is within the stock's average range since 2015 but above the IT services average of 20x, is justifiable because of the company's defensive nature, higher operating margin than competitors', and high RoE.
